345–1409":"1345–1409","1382–1435":"1382–1435","1352–Female":"1352–Deceased","about 1382":"about 1382","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1352":"1352","1382":"1382","1409":"1409","about 1352":"about 1352","England":"England","Furnes Fells, Lancaster, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bardsey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Bedfordshire and Buckinghamshire): altered form of the Lancashire gentry surname   Bardsley  , brought to Buckinghamshire in the 15th century and simplified there from the 16th century onward to <i>Bardsey</i> and <i>Birdsey</i>.","History: The surname (together with the variant <i>Birdseye</i>) was brought to CT from England in the 17th century. Birds Eye frozen food took its brand-name from the founder’s surname, Clarence Frank Birdseye II of Montclair, NJ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bardsley","meanings":["habitational name from Bardsley in Ashton under Lyne, Lancashire, so named from the genitive case of the Old English personal name <i>Beornrēd</i> (composed of the elements <i>beorn</i> ‘young warrior’ + <i>rǣd</i> ‘counsel, advice’) + Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","perhaps also a variant of <b>Barnsley</b>, a habitational name from Barnsley in Gloucestershire, since the early records of the placename show variation between spellings in <i>Barnes-</i>, <i>Barndes-</i>, and <i>Bardes-</i>.","English:"]},{"name":"Birdseye","meanings":["English (Middlesex, Surrey, and Essex): variant of   Birdsey  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":30,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705197,"age":103,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret de Bardsey was born about 1352, in England. She married Thomas Fleming. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"about 1352–":"umbes 1352–Surnud","1345–1409":"1345–1409","1382–1435":"1382–1435","1352–Female":"1352–Surnud","about 1382":"umbes 1382","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1352":"1352","1382":"1382","1409":"1409","abo